Dear Harold,

Thank you for your agreement to proceed with agile methodology for the remote deposit capture project. Transitioning to agile will bring about several changes in how the team operates and how key stakeholders engage, ensuring the success of this initiative.

Changes in Team Operations:
Team Structure:

The team will be organized into cross-functional, self-organizing units comprising developers, testers, and possibly additional roles like UX specialists or performance testers as needed. This structure promotes collaboration and collective ownership of deliverables.
Iterative Development:

Instead of a linear, sequential approach, the team will work in short, time-boxed iterations (typically 2-4 weeks). Each iteration will deliver a potentially shippable product increment, starting with the most critical features and progressively building upon them.
Daily Stand-ups:

The team will conduct daily stand-up meetings (or scrums) to synchronize activities, discuss progress, and identify any impediments. These brief meetings foster transparency, communication, and quick issue resolution.
Continuous Feedback and Adaptation:

Agile encourages frequent feedback loops with stakeholders. This means regular demos or showcases of completed functionality, allowing stakeholders to provide feedback early and often. This feedback informs subsequent iterations and ensures alignment with business goals.
Changes in Stakeholder Engagement:
Active Participation:

Stakeholders, including yourself, Tricia, and other business leaders, will be actively involved throughout the project. This involvement includes attending sprint reviews, providing feedback on deliverables, and prioritizing features based on business value.
Prioritization and Flexibility:

Agile allows for flexibility in prioritizing features based on changing market conditions or customer feedback. Stakeholders will need to engage in regular prioritization sessions to ensure that the team is delivering the most valuable functionality early in the project lifecycle.
Clear Communication Channels:

Effective communication channels will be established to facilitate continuous dialogue between the team and stakeholders. This ensures that any changes in requirements or business priorities are communicated promptly and understood by all parties.
Training and Support Needs:
Given that the team is new to agile, here are the specific support needs:

Agile Training:

The team will benefit from comprehensive agile training to familiarize themselves with agile principles, roles (such as Scrum Master and Product Owner), ceremonies (like sprint planning and retrospectives), and best practices. This foundational training will ensure that everyone is aligned on agile concepts and methodologies.
Technical Training:

As noted in the case study, the team lacks experience in mobile development, performance testing, and UX expertise. Additional technical training or workshops in these areas would enhance the team's capabilities and readiness to deliver high-quality software.
Coaching and Mentoring:

Engaging an agile coach or mentor, at least initially, could provide valuable guidance in applying agile principles effectively within the context of this project. This support can help the team navigate challenges and optimize their agile practices for maximum productivity and quality.
Conclusion:
With your support and commitment, adopting agile for the remote deposit capture project will enable Blue Bank to deliver a superior, customer-centric service that meets our business objectives. I am confident that with the necessary training and support, the team will successfully embrace agile practices and deliver a successful outcome.

